type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix. Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> contains all the eigenvalues of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a unique <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex> called the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Jordan Canonical Form</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> such that the following all hold:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\sim \mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
<fr:li>For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\sim  B]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)=\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (B)]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
<fr:li>The <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {JCF}}\nolimits (A)]]></fr:tex> is a block diagonal matrix consisting of <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-005A.xml"
addr="ra-005A"
title="Jordan block">Jordan blocks</fr:link>.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
